  "summary": "Hercule Poirot discusses the death of Rosalind Claude with Inspector Spence, arguing that she was murdered rather than committing suicide. Poirot reveals that a call was made from a public telephone booth at Wormsley Vicarage to the Sheepfold apartment at 10:15 PM on Tuesday, suggesting someone was present in the flat. He contends that the woman seen wearing an orange scarf was not Rosalind Claude, which shifts the motive and identity of the killer. Poirot classifies the three deaths in the case differently: he views the death of Enoch Dorrington (Charles Trenton) as an accident, one death as a suicide, and Rosalind Claude's death as a premeditated murder. He suggests there are two distinct murderers and leaves Spence to await a letter from overseas.\n\nPoirot then visits Madame Claude to question her regarding her husband’s morphine addiction, which she explains began during the war due to overwork and neuralgia. When asked if she met anyone at the public telephone booth on the night she called Lynn Marchmont, Madame Claude recalls borrowing two pence from a woman exiting the booth. She describes the woman as looking like an actress wearing an orange scarf, noting that the woman's face seemed familiar, as if she were someone who had already passed away. Meanwhile, Lynn Marchmont decides she must visit the Longrein Residence to speak with Rolly face-to-face, feeling that a storm is approaching and that she is about to say goodbye to her current way of life.",
